Q: What is Selenium WebDriver:
A:
    WebDriver is one of the component in selenium.
    WebDriver is a java interface which has many implementation classes like ChromeDriver, FirefoxDriver, EdgeDriver etc.
    WebDriver is an API(Application Programming Interface) which is used to automate the web application for testing purposes.

    WebDriver (I)
            RemoteWebDriver (C)
                    ChromeDriver (C)
                    FirefoxDriver (C)
                    EdgeDriver (C)
                    SafariDriver (C)
                    OperaDriver (C)
                    HtmlUnitDriver (C)
                    PhantomJSDriver (C)
            TakesScreenshot (I)
            JavaScriptExecutor (I)
            HasCapabilities (I)
            Interactive (I)

Q: How WebDriver is interacted with the browser?
A: Selenium WebDriver interacts with browser using browser-specific driver executables like ChromeDriver or GeckoDriver.
   WebDriver sends commands through W3C WebDriver protocol, the driver translates them into browser actions,
   browser executes them and sends response back to Selenium.

Q: Why we create a Maven Project for Selenium WebDriver?
A: Apache maven is a build and project management tool used mainly for java projects
    	i. Manages project build (compile, test, package)
    	ii. Handles dependencies automatically
    	iii. Uses a standard project structure
    	iv. Integrates well with selenium, TestNG, Jenkins

Q: Different types of methods used in Selenium WebDriver?

    1. Browser Control Methods
        i. get(String url): Opens the specified URL in the browser.
        ii. getTitle(): Retrieves the title of the current page.
        iii. getCurrentUrl(): Retrieves the URL of the current page.
        iv. getPageSource(): Retrieves the HTML source code of the current page.
        v. close(): Closes the current browser window.
        vi. quit(): Closes all browser windows and ends the WebDriver session.

    2. Navigation Methods: Used with --> driver.navigate()
        i. to(String url): Navigates to the specified URL.
        ii. back(): Navigates back to the previous page.
        iii. forward(): Navigates forward to the next page.
        iv. refresh(): Refreshes the current page.

    3. Window Management Methods: Used with --> driver.manage().window()
        i. maximize(): Maximizes the browser window.
        ii. minimize(): Minimizes the browser window.
        iii. fullscreen(): Makes the browser window full screen.
        iv. setSize(Dimension targetSize): Sets the size of the browser window to the specified dimensions.
        v. getSize(): Retrieves the current size of the browser window.
        vi. setPosition(Point targetPosition): Sets the position of the browser window to the specified coordinates.
        vii. getPosition(): Retrieves the current position of the browser window.

    4. Timeouts Methods: Used with --> driver.manage().timeouts()
        i. implicitlyWait(Duration time): Sets the implicit wait timeout for finding elements.
        ii. pageLoadTimeout(Duration time): Sets the timeout for page loading.
        iii. scriptTimeout(Duration time): Sets the timeout for asynchronous scripts.

    5. Element Finding Methods: Used with --> driver.findElement() or driver.findElements()
        i. findElement(By by): Finds the first web element using the specified locator strategy (e.g., By.id, By.name, By.xpath).
        ii. findElements(By by): Finds all web elements matching the specified locator strategy and returns a list of WebElements.

    6. Frame Methods: Used with --> driver.switchTo().frame()
        i. frame(int index): Switches to the frame by its index.
        ii. frame(String nameOrId): Switches to the frame by its name or ID.
        iii. frame(WebElement frameElement): Switches to the frame using a WebElement reference
        iv. defaultContent(): Switches back to the main document from a frame.
        v. parentFrame(): Switches to the parent frame of the current frame.

    7. Alert Methods: Used with --> driver.switchTo().alert()
        i. accept(): Accepts the alert (clicks OK).
        ii. dismiss(): Dismisses the alert (clicks Cancel).
        iii. getText(): Retrieves the text from the alert.
        iv. sendKeys(String keysToSend): Sends text to the alert's input field (if present).

    8. Window Handling Methods: Used with --> driver.getWindowHandle() and driver.getWindowHandles()
        i. getWindowHandle(): Retrieves the unique identifier of the current browser window, allowing you to switch back to it later if needed.
        ii. getWindowHandles(): Retrieves a set of unique identifiers for all open browser windows, allowing you to switch between them.

    9. Cookie Management Methods: Used with --> driver.manage()
        i. addCookie(Cookie cookie): Adds a cookie to the current domain.
        ii. getCookies(): Retrieves all cookies for the current domain as a Set of Cookie objects.
        iii. deleteCookie(Cookie cookie): Deletes a specific cookie by passing a Cookie object.
        iv. deleteCookieNamed(String name): Deletes a cookie by its name.
        v. deleteAllCookies(): Deletes all cookies for the current domain.

    10. Screenshot Methods: Used with --> TakesScreenshot interface
        i. getScreenshotAs(OutputType<T> target): Captures a screenshot of the current browser window and returns it in the specified output type (e.g., OutputType.FILE, OutputType.BASE64).
            Eg: TakesScreenshot ts = (TakesScreenshot) driver;
                File src = ts.getScreenshotAs(OutputType.FILE);

    11. JavaScriptExecutor Methods: Used with --> JavaScriptExecutor interface
        i. executeScript(String script, Object... args): Executes the specified JavaScript code in the context of the current page and returns the result.
        ii. executeAsyncScript(String script, Object... args): Executes asynchronous JavaScript code in the context of the current page and returns the result once the script has completed.

    12. Wait Methods: Used with --> WebDriverWait and ExpectedConditions
        i. WebDriverWait wait = new WebDriverWait(driver, Duration.ofSeconds(10));
           wait.until(ExpectedConditions.visibilityOfElementLocated(By.id("elementId")));
        ii. WebDriverWait wait = new WebDriverWait(driver, Duration.ofSeconds(10));
            wait.until(ExpectedConditions.elementToBeClickable(By.id("elementId")));

Q: Selenium WebDriver Architecture:
A: Selenium WebDriver follows a client-server architecture.
   The WebDriver client translates the commands from your script into HTTP requests following the W3C WebDriver protocol.
   These Http requests are sent to the browser-specific driver (e.g., ChromeDriver), which acts as a server.
   Finally the browser drivers interpret the http request and control the actual browsers, carrying out the actions.
   The browser executes the commands and returns the response to the driver, which is relayed back to the WebDriver client.

   Q: Why W3c WebDriver protocol?
   A: The W3C WebDriver protocol is a standardized way for WebDriver clients to communicate with browser drivers,
       ensuring compatibility across different browsers and programming languages.

   Q: What is browser driver?
   A: A browser driver is a separate executable that WebDriver uses to control a specific browser.
      Each browser has its own driver that implements the WebDriver protocol to translate commands from the client into actions performed by the browser.

# Program 1
/*
    1. Launch the browser and open the URL https://www.google.com/
    2. Verify the title of the page is "Google"
    3. Close the browser
 */
import org.openqa.selenium.WebDriver;
import org.openqa.selenium.chrome.ChromeDriver;

public class com.akbar._01_basics._01_Introduction {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        // Step 1: Launch the browser and open the URL https://www.google.com/
        WebDriver driver = new ChromeDriver();
        // WebDriver driver = new FirefoxDriver(); // For Firefox
        // WebDriver driver = new EdgeDriver(); // For Edge

        driver.get("https://www.google.com/");

        // Step 2: Verify the title of the page is "Google"
        String expectedTitle = "Google";

        // Retrieve the actual title from the opened page
        String actualTitle = driver.getTitle();

        // Compare expected vs actual and print the result.
        // equals() is used for exact match. If you want case-insensitive comparison, use equalsIgnoreCase().
        if (actualTitle.equals(expectedTitle)) {
            System.out.println("Title verification passed!");
        } else {
            System.out.println("Title verification failed! Expected: " + expectedTitle + ", but got: " + actualTitle);
        }

        // Step 3: Close the browser
        // quit() closes all browser windows and safely ends the session.
        driver.quit();
    }
}

Q: What is locator in Selenium WebDriver?
A: A locator in Selenium is used to identify and find web elements on a webpage so automation scripts can interact with them.

  For example, Selenium uses locators to:
        Click a button
        Enter text into a textbox
        Select a dropdown value
        Read text from a page

  Types:
    1. ID: Locates an element by its unique ID attribute.
    2. Name: Locates an element by its name attribute.
    3. Class Name: Locates elements by their class attribute.
    4. Tag Name: Locates elements by their HTML tag name.
    5. Link Text: Locates a link element by its exact text.
    6. Partial Link Text: Locates a link element by partial text match.
    7. CSS Selector: Locates elements using CSS syntax.
    8. XPath: Locates elements using XML path expressions.

Q: What is WebElement in Selenium WebDriver?
A: A WebElement in Selenium represents a single HTML element present on a webpage.
   After locating an element using a locator, Selenium stores that element inside a WebElement object so we can perform actions on it.

   Common Methods of WebElement:
    i. click(): Clicks on the element.
    ii. sendKeys(String keysToSend): Types the specified text into the element (e.g., input fields).
    iii. getText(): Retrieves the visible text of the element.
    iv. clear(): Clears the text from an input field.
    v. isDisplayed(): Checks if the element is visible on the page.
    vi. isEnabled(): Checks if the element is enabled and can be interacted with.
    vii. isSelected(): Checks if the element (e.g., checkbox or radio button) is selected.
    viii. getAttribute(String name): Retrieves the value of a specified attribute of the element.

Q: What is the difference between findElement() and findElements() methods in Selenium WebDriver?
A:
findElement():
     findElement() is used to locate a single web element on the page.
     It returns the first matching element as a WebElement object. If no element is found, it throws a NoSuchElementException.

findElements():
     findElements() is used to locate multiple web elements on the page.
     It returns a List of WebElement objects that match the specified locator. If no elements are found,
         it returns an empty list instead of throwing an exception.

Q: Different ways to identify the locator using CSS Selector?
A: CSS Selector is a powerful way to locate elements using CSS syntax. Here are different ways to identify locators using CSS Selector:
    i. By ID: #idValue
    ii. By Class: .className
    iii. By Tag: tagName
    iv. By Attribute: [attributeName='value']
    v. By Attribute Contains: [attributeName*='value']
    vi. By Attribute Starts With: [attributeName^='value']
    vii. By Attribute Ends With: [attributeName$='value']
    viii. By Multiple Classes: .class1.class2
    ix. By Descendant: parent child
    x. By Child: parent > child
    xi. By Sibling: element1 + element2 (adjacent sibling), element1 ~ element2 (general sibling)
    xii. By Pseudo-classes: :first-child, :last

Q: What is Xpath in Selenium WebDriver?
A: XPath (XML Path Language) is a locator strategy used in Selenium to identify and navigate elements in an HTML document.
   It helps Selenium find web elements on a webpage when attributes like id or name are not available or are dynamic.

Q: What are the different tyepes of Xpath in Selenium WebDriver?
    i. Absolute XPath: It starts from the root of the HTML document and follows a specific path to the target element.
       It is not recommended for use as it is brittle and can break easily if there are any changes in the HTML structure.
                Example: /html/body/div[1]/div[2]/div[1]/h1
       Starts from the root element (/html)
       Uses complete path of the element
       Very lengthy
       Breaks easily if UI structure changes

       Disadvantages
        i. Not reliable
        ii. Hard to maintain
        iii. Any UI change can break it

    ii. Relative XPath: It starts from any element in the document and can be more flexible and robust than absolute XPath.
       It is recommended for use in Selenium.
                Example: //h1[@id='header']
       Starts with //
       Searches element anywhere in DOM
       More flexible and commonly used

       Advantages
        i Easy to write
        ii. More stable
        iii. Preferred in Selenium automation

        >> Absolute xpath starts with /. it represents root node.
        >> Relative xpath starts with //. it represents searching anywhere in the DOM.

        >> Absolute xpath do not use attributes.
        >> Relative xpath uses attributes to locate elements.

        >> Absolute xpath traverse through each node till it reaches the target element.
        >> Relative xpath directly locates the target element using attributes without traversing through each node.

        Syntax:
        //tagname[@attribute='value']

Q: Explain about the Xpath Axes in Selenium WebDriver?
A: XPath axes allow you to navigate the DOM tree relative to a known element. Common axes include:
        i. parent: Selects the parent of the current node.
        //Eg: //input[@id='txtUsername']/parent::form

        ii. child: Selects the children of the current node.
        Eg: //div[@id='divUsername']/child::input
        Note: In practice / is used instead of child:: from the known Xpath.

        iii. ancestor: Selects all ancestors (parent, grandparent, etc.) of the current node.
        Eg //input[@name='txtUsername']/ancestor::form

        iv. descendant: Selects all descendants (children, grandchildren, etc.) of the current node.
        Eg: //form[@id='frmLogin']/descendant::input

        v. following: Selects everything in the document after the closing tag of the current node.
           // Eg: //input[@id='txtUsername']/following::input

           // - preceding: Selects everything in the document before the opening tag of the current node.
           // Eg: //span[text()='Password']/preceding::input

           // - following-sibling: Selects all siblings after the current node.
           // Eg: //input[@id='txtUsername']/following-sibling::span

           // - preceding-sibling: Selects all siblings before the current node.
           // Eg: //span[contains(text(), 'Username')]/preceding-sibling::input

           Some conditional xpaths:
           i. //span[text()>100]
           ii. //span[text()<100]
           iii. //span[text()>=100]
           iv. //span[text()<=100]
           v. //span[text()!=100]

